[1]
Date: Thu, 13 May 2004 1:03:41 EDT
From: Miguel E. Escobar, DVM <Meescobar@aol.com>


Trichomoniasis is a VERY common disease in pigeons and doves, but raptors,
canaries, finches and budgerigar can also host the protozoa. Clean
lofts/aviariums, if they are companion birds, is the best solution.
Dimetridazole and like molecules will take care of the parasite.

--
Miguel E. Escobar, DVM
<Meescobar@aol.com>

******
[2]
Date: Thu, 13 May 2004 09:14:41 -0700 (PDT)
From: Donna Sweet <donnaargus@yahoo.com>


I have also seen trichomoniasis in Great Horned Owls. It may also be
transmitted between pigeons during ritualized courtship feeding in which
the female places her beak in the male's mouth. Affected birds often
display respiratory distress and open-mouthed breathing. Trichomoniasis is
treatable with several drugs such as Emtryl.

--
Donna Sweet
(former Animal Care Supervisor / Acting Curator in a couple of zoological
parks)
<donnaargus@yahoo.com>

