[3]
Date: Fri, 14 May 2004 10:22:37 -0400
From: Mark Pokras <mark.pokras@tufts.edu>


Trichomoniasis is a common finding not only in pigeons and doves, but also
in the birds of prey that may feed upon them. From anecdotal reports, it
is interesting to note that the parasite appears more pathogenic in the
western portion of the country than in the east, especially in birds of
prey. This may be due to strain variations in the parasite or in evolved
resistance in host defenses. Hanson (1969) pointed out that pigeons (and
_Trichomonas_) were introduced to the eastern part of the continent roughly
2 centuries before their introduction to the west coast, and speculated
that this parasite may have contributed significantly to the extinction of
the passenger pigeon.

A few interesting references are appended.

Field Manual of Wildlife Disease, chapter on Trichomonas:
<http://www.nwhc.usgs.gov/pub_metadata/field_manual/chapter_25.pdf>

Pokras, MA, Wheeldon, E and CJ Sedgwick.1993. Trichomoniasis in owls. In
Redig, P.T. et al.(eds).Raptor biomedicine. Univ. of Minnesota Press.pp: 88-91.

Hanson, R.P. 1969. The possible role of infectious agents in the
extinctions of species. In Peregrine Falcon Populations. J.J. Hickey
(ed.) University of Wisconsin Press, Madison, Wisconsin,pp.439-444.

Jessup, D.A. 1980. Trichomoniasis in great horned owls. Modern Veterinary
Practice 61:601-604.

Schulz,T. 1986. Conservation and rehabilitation of the common barn owl.
Proceedings National Wildlife Rehabilitators Association 4th Annual
Meeting, NWRA, Brighton, Illinois. pp.146Â­166.

Schulz,T. University of California at Davis. School of Veterinary
Medicine. Davis, California. 95616.

Stabler, R.M. 1954. Trichomonas gallinae: a review. Experimental
Parasitology 3:368-402.

Tanabe, M. 1925. The cultivation of trichomonads from man, rat and
owl. Journal of Parasitology 12:101-104.

